### 7.1 Distribution of clustering outcomes

**Important:** The coefficient of variation (CV) is *not* the best stability metric here. k-means++ has slightly higher CV (44.43% vs 40.22%) because it produces a **bimodal distribution**: the vast majority of runs cluster tightly at the global optimum (φ ≈ 317), but a handful fail badly. High standard deviation relative to mean inflates CV. In contrast, k-means spreads failures more uniformly across the range, giving it lower CV by the ratio formula — despite being objectively worse. The **ECDF** (panel d, lower right) and **median** values are far more informative: the median k-means++ run (316.97) *equals* the global optimum, while the median k-means run (630.54) is nearly twice as bad.
