## 13. Conclusions

In this project, we implemented both standard k-means and k-means++ from scratch and analyzed the impact of initialization on clustering performance.

The experiments showed that standard k-means is highly sensitive to initialization due to the non-convex nature of the optimization problem. Different random seeds often produced significantly different clustering outcomes, leading to high variability in inertia values and convergence behavior.

In contrast, k-means++ consistently achieved lower inertia and more stable clustering solutions by selecting initial centroids using a probabilistic D²-weighting strategy. This demonstrates how careful algorithm design can improve both empirical performance and optimization stability.

**Theory and Practice Aligned:** Arthur & Vassilvitskii (2007) proved that k-means++ achieves an expected inertia of $ \mathcal{O}(\log k) \times \phi^* $, where $ \phi^* $ is the optimal inertia. Our experiments confirm this theoretical prediction: the advantage of k-means++ over plain k-means grows systematically with the number of clusters $ k $ (Figure 9, Table 2) and with dimensionality $ d $ (Figure 8), consistent with the $ \mathcal{O}(\log k) $ bound. On well-separated clusters, k-means++ achieved 26.9% mean inertia improvement and 30% faster convergence.

Additional experiments on overlapping clusters and high-dimensional real-world datasets further highlighted the importance of initialization in difficult clustering settings. While both algorithms may struggle as cluster overlap increases, k-means++ generally remained more reliable and converged faster across trials.

Overall, the project illustrates a central idea in machine learning optimization: in non-convex problems, randomness and initialization can strongly influence the final empirical risk minimization solution. Careful seeding strategies such as k-means++ provide a simple but highly effective improvement over naive random initialization, with theoretical guarantees and consistent empirical validation across diverse settings.


